Pages = {{993-1005}},
Month = {{OCT 1}},
Abstract = {{We present detailed results of numerical experiments into the nature of
   complete sunspots. The models remain highly idealized but include fully
   nonlinear compressible magnetoconvection in an axisymmetric layer that
   drives energy into an overlying, low-beta plasma. We survey a range of
   parameters in which the resulting magnetoconvection displays the
   formation of pore- and sunspot-like behavior and assess the coronal
   signatures resulting from the energy generated by the
   magnetoconvection. The coronal heating is assumed to be a result of the
   dissipation by an unspecified means of a fraction of the Poynting flux
   entering the corona. The expected signatures in the EUV and soft X-ray
   bandpasses of the Transition Region and Coronal Explorer and
   Yohkoh/SXT, respectively, are examined. This ad hoc coupling of the
   corona to the subphotospheric region results in a dynamical behavior
   that is consistent with recent observational results. This agreement
   demonstrates that even simple coupled modeling can lead to diagnostics
   for investigations of both subphotospheric sunspot structures and
   coronal heating mechanisms.}},
